column110: The transition process from Technomedia to MOOD has not been the smoothest I have been through. Unfortunately, many things fell by the wayside and has left a bias towards changes I would recommend. I believe maybe another year under the MOOD branch would provide a more clear image of expectations, goals,  etc. For now, it seems offering more benefits to the employees would make a greater positive impact. Including a sick bank would be beneficial to those who not only have to take care of themselves, but family members as well. If sick time cannot be offered, then the accrual rate should be raised. Or including company maternity/paternity leave that is financially supported.

column99: currently, to provide value to all stakeholders
column110: Most employees at Mood are severely overworked and underpaid. I am currently making less money with 7 years of tenure at Mood than those graduating today with the same level of education and no prior experience. MMNA is headquartered in one of the most expensive places to live in the country, and full-time pay at Mood is not enough to make ends meet. I believe pay is at the center of a lot of discontent with working at Mood.  Money is not a new problem here. This company is run on boomer-era sales methods that are quickly becoming obsolete. Our web-based sales outside of Pandora (a dying music medium) are close to nonexistent, with several failed attempts in the last 5 years. Our tech is consistently behind by a decade or more (the recent implementation of Oracle Service Cloud and Harmony were a huge step in the right direction). Our product team does not take client or customer service feedback into consideration when designing new products and services, though recent events are showing an improvement.   I'm personally not confident in the future success or direction of the company without seeing major changes to structure, compensation, and communicated company goals. Appeasing stakeholders by consolidating our assets is fine, but employees are not seeing direction from leadership relative to our roles.  I really am passionate for working at Mood with my team members. I want the company to succeed, and I'll keep working my hardest to make that happen. But I wish (and hope) that leadership would invest more in its people; those who have worked hard through the tough times and have the ideas and initiatives we need to take action on in order to survive.

column110: Transparency in everything.  I think we are getting there as a company.  I'd personally like to know what changes are happening in the company, when are they happening and why the need for the specific change (Example: moving a department to another city or even reducing a departments workforce).  I'd like to know any outside forces affecting our company and how we plan to react (Example: competitors offering a new game changing product).  When talking about our financial status or anything complex and specialized in Global Town Halls, summarize the data in layperson's terms.  I'd also like to know why employees haven't received raises in a some time.  I think it would help moral to explain the reasoning behind some company decisions.  I feel like I'm a greater and more important part of the company when I'm given more insight into our decisions.  Only to the extent that leadership is able to share, however.  I understand certain situations can't be discussed.

column110: Culture - A company's core values need to be established and ingrained by leadership. Mood Media does not have a positive culture; maybe among leadership, but it is not shared and shown throughout the company. If we truly embraced a positive culture, we would be more understanding of our employees and clients needs and work towards a MUCH BETTER client experience. Our clients are why we all have jobs! Shouldn't we be more concerned about their satisfaction and overall experience? If we treated our own children/family in the way Mood treats our clients, our children would move out as far away as possible, as quickly as possible. Shouldn't we want them to stick around and keep coming over? We Win as One means nothing if we do not believe it. Saying it and having it written means nothing unless it is practiced and enforced.

column110: Mood needs to stop being so attached to old fashioned products and start thinking of more inovative and competitive ideas. When looking at what our competitors have to offers, it becomes obvious that Mood fails to provide solutions for the future, instead focusing on old fashioned services such as satellite. Mood also needs to invest in the people that actually bring value to the company, as our turnover is unacceptably high. We can keep investing money in marketing and travel expenses for the same 20 people to go out and give motivational speeches to employees, but if we continue to overwork and underpay our employees, nobody's going to want to work for Mood. That is already true in the country where I'm based, where Mood was considered a good employer until 2 years ago, when it got the reputation that people and poorly paid and that their job description only covers 20% of what they'll end up doing. The executives are under a very false impression that they're saving money by paying employees less than what they're worth, but for the lower management people such as myself, it is painfully obvious we are losing clients and therefore money due to the turnover of people that does not allow for our people to become very good at their job.

column99: I will honestly be surprised if this company still exists in 10 years
column110: I honestly don't think there is a single change. This company has to do a complete overhaul in how it values its employees and our time. When I interviewed for my position, I was led to believe that there would be room to grow. I realized very quickly that this is a dead end job. I have been here for almost 3 years, have not seen a single raise, not even a cost of living adjustment which is ridiculous. If I had known this would be the case, I would not have taken this job. I am angry by how management runs this organization, the appalling lack of communication, how no one is willing to take responsibility for their mistakes or do their actual job. Why should I do anything other than the bare minimum that is required of me when I am not compensated for my work? Management likes to say how this is a dream job and imply that we are replaceable. That's a very naive way to look at things. Even if I were to be replaced, you would then have to hire someone, train them, get them used to the job, which could take months, maybe a year. You are then wasting money and the time of your employees by piling more work on them without compensation. Cutbacks were made, offices were closed, we were given even more work and yet no raise. I am given more work than other employees because some can't be trusted with an account - then why are they still employed by this company? This place needs to fix itself and I would not recommend to anyone that they work here.

column110: Simplify & streamline processes (training, accountability and measured), break down Department SILOS, cultivate a culture of "Extreme Ownership" (Book on Leadership and Winning in Business). Put Client satisfaction FIRST over Processes and 20+ email chains not taking ownership, take charge, and lead just to ship or return the wrong part (for example or) or schedule a service call or install. We have become a company putting inventory process (dotting i's and crossing t's? ahead of client satisfaction. Technicians hear it everyday as the face of the company when they walk into meet the client and the client is already upset complaining about how long they were on hold, how long it took to schedule the install/service call, or the incorrect billing they received.  We as a company need to do and be better to keep a competitive edge. We have a lot of work to do to reach our potential. I know I am committed continue striving to be my very Best everyday.

column110: Prove the employees mean something to the company by compensating them fairly for the work they do. Mood decided to consolidate depts and centralize in Austin, which is 9% above the national average for cost of living and yet refuses to offer livable wages or even provide performance raises. We also need more visibility into where the money is going if not to the employees who make this business happen?

column110: To be more focused on clients.  For example our voice team used to have relationships with the clients that handled the messaging.  We would make contact with them every message cycle (typically 1-3 months).  This would keep the client happy about paying for the service even if they were not changing the messages.  I feel this was especially effective for the smaller one off locations as we were getting $30-$40 per month for a tape player used for on hold messages that could be playing the same thing for years.  But since we instituted the new system in voice a few years ago that we no longer are proactive in checking in with these clients many of them have cancelled.  I really think when we had a more direct relationship with our clients the retention rate was much higher for these smaller clients.

column110: I believe the organisation needs a major restructure and a new leader with a clear direction. We struggle for direction, have no achievable goal and depend extensively on a small key of lower grade employees to keep the business afloat. These select few are doing roles and responsibilities that are far beyond what they are supposed to do and or have any training to do, eg. finances, IT, Customer support, Stock.   Roles and responsibilities are not clear and departments are the first to assign any work to individuals even if they have no training to do the part or related the the relative department. On a consistent basis being a 1/4 of the week at a minimum the business is empty with staff working from home which impacts on the direction of the business.   I believe the best solution to solve this issue is to recruit a new top manager who will bring a clear approach and relevant contacts who can push Mood into the new decade.

column110: Since the introduction of the Apple iPod Moodmedia has lacked technology direction in the music arena, instead relying on the past, preferring to sit on the fence watching other technology driven companies succeed with great products, easy to use software and apps. Moodmedia has framed itself in a closed box preferring to look back at the past now finding itself unable to compete with both small and large companies.  Moodmedia management at all levels should be reviewed with radical changes made there. Under performing Sales staff should be reviewed. Helpdesk/Customer Service Position Descriptions should be re-written reflecting  wider responsibilities, increased workloads from previous amalgamations of positions including those lost not reflected in current salaries.  With 1.3 Billion people not enough emphasis has been made into the Chinese retail market which is far from mature compared to the US.  Moodmedia should actively be poaching staff from popular companies or young students who can create, design, engineer both hardware and code great software. Moodmedia should employ staff who can do, not just maybe.   Moodmedia Finance Accounts should be independently audited similar to government auditors.

column110: I have only recently joined the company so I'm still learning the role and don't have a thorough knowledge of the company's history. Having said that, I would explore would be ways to release the MVP 195 to the market, Electricians, integrators, installers and even individual shop owners.  We provide a subscription service that's our income stream. The client can manage the visuals. This could be at various levels, for example if an integrator has many clients and manages their video, then that is one level of membership along with a subscription service per product sold. An individual customer would have a different level of membership.   There could also be a training platform that customer sign up for either individual training videos or subscription membership where customers pay a small fee to watch training videos on the product that they purchased. This is about creating multiple income streams for the company.  Providing a subscription visual display solution will enable Integrators, installers, electricians and the like a viable option for consideration as they find solutions for their customer's needs. This will broaden our market share and increase our income as well as further promote our brand.  I know that right now, the tech guy at the local school or place of worship would have a use for our product or service I think that we need to enable them to easy use and manage our service on a subscription basis.  Thanks for the opportunity to speak and share my thoughts.

If I had been asked to take this survey several months ago, I would have completely different answers than the ones I have submitted today. I've enjoyed working here since I started in 2018 and have grown and thrived as an AR Specialist (the name of my position prior to the departmental changes). I've become one of the "go-to" individuals on the team for all billing questions, and even some invoicing questions even though I only started invoicing for HEB a few months ago. I informally stepped into the "go-to" roll when Rusty Fisher left Mood last year. I sincerely enjoy coming into work, doing what I know how to do, doing it well and exceeding expectations, working on special projects as well (while doing my best to maintain acceptable metrics simultaneously).  As Texas is an "at will" state, it's hard to speak on any discomfort or distress even when it's important to vocalize. However, the employee experience wasn't considered during the changes. No AR employees were consulted or surveyed prior to any changes being made, & the lack of consideration has severely deflated my confidence in Mood as an organization, as it has done for many others within the department.  The recent AR departmental changes have created visual unrest and we are all struggling greatly to train in brand new specializations for which we did not originally sign on with Mood to perform. On top of everyone being spread very thin, tasks & client sensitive items are falling behind and are being done incorrectly for these reasons. The changes are negatively impacting the employees because everyone is expected to perform multiple new specializations at the regular pace of business. The client experience is suffering because they now have to build a relationship with a new Mood employee rather than one they are already have confidence in & are comfortable working with. Many new errors are occurring on all sides of AR and it all negatively impacts the client.  I do still enjoy working at Mood. I love my team and my supervisors, I enjoy the work I was hired to do, I thoroughly love being put on special projects, and being the "go-to" person for billing & some invoicing. Helping my teammates thrive and feel supported is very gratifying and I take every opportunity I am able to to do so. Fortunately I also have an excellent teammate who supports me (Thomas Bailey), and helps others when I am unable to do so.  As previously stated, I do understand that every company has a bottom line, certain goals, and requirements, but none of it should not come at the cost of the employee. At this point, I would not recommend anyone join the organization's AR team.

column110: Invest more in people to do the jobs that require human thought and not think technology will solve everything.  Yes being more efficient with technology overall is critical and I wholeheartedly support the ERP effort, but particularly in the creative department, I've yet to find a computer or AI that can be as creative as a human being.    Our Premier accounts demand creativity from us and our biggest USP and the value we bring to clients is in our ideas and our creativity. That only comes from having enough PEOPLE to do the jobs being asked of us.        We cannot be creative when every day is a fire fight just to survive the working day. We need to be an ideas factory and invest in a creative culture to become a business that truly understands what it takes to be "creative".  Only then will we attract the best talent to create the best work, and ultimately, win bigger clients who are willing to pay what it takes for our creative services.    That's how we stop this race to the bottom where we are simply a commodity line in a procurement spreadsheet when the only question asked of us is: "how cheap can you go".    Instead, lets re-frame the conversation to be:  "how much do I need to pay for your incredible services".  Wouldn't that be a nice place to be.....

column110: CULTURE! Mood Media right now is the perfect example of Peter Drucker's famous statement: Culture eats strategy for breakfast. We still have good potential as a company, we still have people who are onboard and ready to build on that great potential, we master the theory of doing the right things but then in practice, somehow we fail in delivering results. Elevate the Experience for our clients and each other has to be more than just a statement: it should become what the company lives every day and should be reflected in all the decisions that are made at all levels.

column110: Salary increases - at the very least cost of living raises would be nice. many of us have not had salary increases for 5+ years and the promise is always there that it will come but instead more work comes and you are expected to tackle it without any kind of incentive. Because I have integrity, I do the best I can at my job (with or without a raise) but I imagine there are employees who are in quite a slump and don't try as hard because there is no incentive. I'm having financial struggles at the moment but I still come to work every day and do my best. I've been a loyal employee for over 13 years and in the beginning I was rewarded for my achievements. But as time went on and the company wasn't doing very well and then we merged with other entities, some changes came our way and I was rewarded but only because I was in a management position. Friends I have who work elsewhere have bonus opportunities and I have a salary that might have looked like a lot on paper but the reality is a dollar doesn't stretch quite like it used to. I would consider myself one of the top performers on my team but I barely get  a thank you for that. If I'm doing something wrong, no one has said anything. So I'm stuck in limbo, wondering if I'm going to keep getting the same salary as the world around us gets more and more expensive. Our department rarely does anything for us as a team either. Sometimes it feels very thankless and I know management gets busy and forgets, but still .... not getting at least cost of living raises or merit increases (which I still, dutifully, work hard for!) and feeling like an increase does not sit in my future brings the morale down. This is true, I would say, for almost everyone on my team.

column110: When a customer calls in to the call center , have a live person answer within 4 rings.  The Biggest complaint I get is that  people call us , get into the menu , select  an option and are then put on hold for very long periods of time .  I have been told that our clients have taken their business elsewhere because of this.  They are also given the option to leave a call back number , but never get a call back.  This includes very large accounts.  I can clearly see that new sales are not keeping up with the loss of existing clients.  We may still be supplying the music to some of these clients but losing other business such as upgrades to sound systems, new drive thru eq. Etc. Or losing opportunities to supply our services   and products to existing clients that are opening new stores because they have lost faith in our abilities to meet their expectations.  I'm sad to say that people have grown used to slow or poor service , not just with MOOD but all corporation owned business. Maybe it's just the way business is done now , but it's sad.  Having a live person answer the phones by  the first 4 rings  instead of a machine answering would be a big improvement . It's the biggest complaint I hear on a daily basis.

column110: There are too many to list... But since you asked for just one.  Customer service response times... it is unacceptable that it takes 10-14 days before a call can be dispatched and a service technician arrive onsite from the time a customer calls stating they're having equipment issues.  The response time it takes for one to answer the phone in customer service is unacceptable.  The canned response of "please contact billing" because you're behind on your bill and that's why you don't have any music. Not true most of the time, but this is what the customers are being told.  WHAT???     If you really want to change this business, then take care of the customer and back what the great solutions the outside/inside sales representatives are presenting.  Stop allowing 10-14 days at best to be our standard practice for a technician to show up onsite.  Whom in their right mind would think this is okay? If we're truly presenting a total solution that can change the customers business... emotion, memorable, more engaging with their customer, etc., And... we leave these systems down for 10-14 or even more days, well we've just cost our clients revenue because our solutions certainly weren't working therefore Mood wasn't helping the client connect & engage with their client on a deeper more memorable level.  Fix this please.

column110: El principal cambio que creo mejoraría la posición de la compañia es la unificación de los sistemas de Visual y Audio. En particular el sistema de provisión de Mvision es poco eficiente y poco claro, depende mucho de procesos manuales y no es claro para los afiliados tampoco. Creo que en este sentido la implementación de Harmony es un gran paso adelante que va a mejorar el servicio que proveemos sustancialmente. Creo que debería ser un objetivo principal de la compañia migrar a todos nuestros cliente que usan sistemas Mvision y Profusion a Harmony.

column110: Paying the employees a competitive pay. I have spent most of my 7 years at Mood doing the work of 1.5 - 2 people due to the high turn over in my department. The plethora of responsiblities of a Project Manager at Mood Media along with the work load should have the salary of at least 60,000. The reason I stay at Mood Media is because I like what I do, my teammates and the flexibility that is provided. I know money is not everything (that is why I stay here)  but it sure would help to have a pay increase that is competitive to the market. If employees were paid more, they would stay longer, be able to maintain a good quality of life and be happier.

column110: Start promote employees based on their personal skills and diplomas and quit nepotism. In my country's office, Mood's leadership is one happy family. I have seen how a manager of a certain random department can become overnight without any qualifications or skills in that domain, an HR manager. I have seen in 5 years since I am with Mood at least a few jobs that were handed without any restraints, not even a cover up, the interviews were just a facade. It is unacceptable. Start listening to solutions employees come up with. Start chasing the right solutions instead of the big profit. Start rewarding the people that truly put their bones to work only to fill a handful of people's bank accounts. Start caring about people and they will be happier at work and more productive. Start being human and respect every single employee no matter its role. Start keeping your promises or don't take them. Start giving certifications and courses for your employees just like you mentioned in the survey questions (I have never heard of skill development courses inside this company ever). Start investing in a more intelligent way. Start being logical rather then chasing the bigger numbers on a shorter therm. Start respecting people.

column110: Inefficiencies - In the process of onboarding a new client or new service added into our system, have we counted the number of hands it takes to get it from the signed paper until we bill it? Wow! There are so many touches in that process which lengthens the time of getting a new client as well as increasing the margin of error in doing so.  There's room for improvement on accountability. We need better buy in and ownership with issues and mistakes. There are so many people and so many hands in one process, no one takes ownership and responsibility. It's hard to understand where problems occurred, blame is thrown around and more often than not, we never discover what happened. We are reactive versus proactive. Instead of having 20 links in a single chain, why not have 20 chains of smaller, multiple links. Empower people to do more which would solve so many things beyond simply being more effective and efficient.
